            <div type="edition" subtype="transcription" ana="b1">
                <p xml:lang="heb">עליב מסכינה<lb/>די מדעם ביש<lb/>בצול א<gap reason="illegible" quantity="1" unit="character"/>
               <unclear cert="low">ד</unclear>
               <gap reason="illegible" quantity="1" unit="character"/>
                    <gap reason="illegible" quantity="1" unit="character"/>ה<lb/>מתתיה לא <supplied reason="omitted">ל</supplied>חרב<lb/>שלם לשלם</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" ana="b1">
                <p>Unfortunate (and) poor … that something bad …  in all A[.]D[.] [.] H Mattathias,
                    not by sword … Peace, in peace.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" ana="b1">
                <p>The word שלום as found in funerary inscriptions from this time period, should be
                    understood as a standard blessing, but also potentially to include a magical
                    element, wishing peace to the deceased individual's soul or aimed at protecting
                    the person who buried him or those who read the inscription. Thus, unfortunate
                    and poor Mattathias hopes that mentioning the word peace twice might afford him
                    some protection. It is possible that this was written during the First Revolt in
                    70 CE and Mattathias faced the danger of death in battle.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
